Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/20/2026
Notes: Gothic period live-action; candlelight and deep shadow; closed cast; narrator addresses camera as confessional frame

===

FADE IN:

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

A spare, candlelit room. Dark wood. A single chair faces us. 

NARRATOR sits close — a lean man in his thirties, pale skin, dark disordered hair, sharp restless eyes, plain black waistcoat and shirtsleeves. Period dress. He leans toward us with unnatural calm.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He almost smiles.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

A shuttered chamber. Thick darkness. An OLD MAN sleeps in a high bed — elderly, thin, white hair, nightshirt. One eye shows in the dim: a pale blue vulture eye, filmed over.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his eye! yes, it was this!

The filmed blue eye seems to find the dark.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold; and so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR, still to camera, eyes bright with pride.

NARRATOR
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

INT. HALL OUTSIDE BEDROOM - NIGHT

Midnight. A narrow hall. NARRATOR stands at a closed door, dark lantern in hand — a tin dark-lantern, shut tight. He turns the latch — oh, so gently — and opens the door a crack.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And every night, about midnight, I turned the latch of his door and opened it—oh, so gently!

He eases the closed lantern through, then his head — slowly, slowly.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And then, when I had made an opening sufficient for my head, I put in a dark lantern, all closed, closed, that no light shone out, and then I thrust in my head. I moved it slowly—very, very slowly, so that I might not disturb the old man's sleep. It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

From the door crack: the OLD MAN asleep. NARRATOR's fingers undo the lantern a hair. A single thin ray seeks the pillow.

The eye is closed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I undid the lantern cautiously—oh, so cautiously—cautiously (for the hinges creaked)—I undid it just so much that a single thin ray fell upon the vulture eye. And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Morning light at the shutters. NARRATOR enters boldly, hearty, kind. The OLD MAN sits up, frail, the filmed eye half-lidded.

NARRATOR
And how have you passed the night?

The OLD MAN murmurs a thin reply. NARRATOR smiles, touches his shoulder with affection.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Every morning, when the day broke, I went boldly into the chamber, and spoke courageously to him, calling him by name in a hearty tone, and inquiring how he has passed the night. So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR leans in, triumphant.

NARRATOR
Ha!—would a madman have been so wise as this?

INT. HALL OUTSIDE BEDROOM - NIGHT

The eighth night. NARRATOR at the door again — slower than a watch's minute hand. Sweat at his temple. A private chuckle escapes him.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. A watch's minute hand moves more quickly than did mine. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph. To think that there I was, opening the door, little by little, and he not even to dream of my secret deeds or thoughts. I fairly chuckled at the idea—

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Pitch black. Shutters fastened. The OLD MAN stirs on the bed, startled.

NARRATOR freezes in the opening, head in, lantern still closed. He does not draw back. He pushes on — steadily, steadily.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
—and perhaps he heard me; for he moved on the bed suddenly, as if startled. Now you may think that I drew back—but no. His room was as black as pitch with the thick darkness, for the shutters were close fastened, through fear of robbers, and so I knew that he could not see the opening of the door, and I kept pushing it on steadily, steadily.

NARRATOR's thumb slips on the tin fastening.

A small metallic sound.

The OLD MAN springs up in bed.

OLD MAN
Who's there?

Silence. NARRATOR does not move a muscle. The OLD MAN sits upright in the dark, listening.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

A long hold: the dark room, the seated figure, NARRATOR's eye in the crack. Time stretches. A faint death-watch tick in the wall.

Then — a slight groan. Low. Stifled.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal terror. It was not a groan of pain or of grief—oh, no!—it was the low stifled sound that arises from the bottom of the soul when overcharged with awe. I knew the sound well.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR, quieter, almost pitying — then a flicker of cruel amusement.

NARRATOR
Many a night, just at midnight, when all the world slept, it has welled up from my own bosom. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled at heart.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The OLD MAN still upright, staring into blackness.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had been trying to fancy them causeless, but could not. He had been saying to himself—

OLD MAN
(whispered, to himself)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Yes, he had been trying to comfort himself with these suppositions: but he had found all in vain. All in vain; because Death, in approaching him had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

NARRATOR waits. Still no lie-down. At last he opens a very, very little crevice in the lantern — stealthily.

A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open — wide, wide open.

NARRATOR's face behind the ray: fury rising.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It was open—wide, wide open—and I grew furious as I gazed upon it. I saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones; but I could see nothing else of the old man's face or person: for I had directed the ray as if by instinct, precisely upon the damned spot.

A low, dull, quick sound — like a watch enveloped in cotton. The HEARTBEAT. Soft at first.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And have I not told you that what you mistake for madness is but over-acuteness of the sense?—now, I say, there came to my ears a low, dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man's heart. It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier into courage.

NARRATOR holds still. Scarcely breathes. The ray steady on the eye. The heartbeat grows quicker — louder.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But even yet I refrained and kept still. I scarcely breathed. I held the lantern motionless. Meantime the hellish tattoo of the heart increased. It grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR, voice tightening, marking each word.

NARRATOR
The old man's terror must have been extreme! It grew louder, I say, louder every moment!—do you mark me well? I have told you that I am nervous: so I am.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The heartbeat pounds. NARRATOR still frozen in the door.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror. Yet, for some minutes longer I refrained and stood still. But the beating grew louder, louder! I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man's hour had come!

With a loud yell NARRATOR throws open the lantern and leaps into the room.

The OLD MAN shrieks once — once only.

NARRATOR drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him.

Silence of struggle under the bed. NARRATOR stands over it — then smiles gaily.

Beneath the bed: the heart still beats on. Muffled. Many minutes.

NARRATOR listens, head tilted, patient. The muffled beat continues... continues... then fades... ceases.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then smiled gaily, to find the deed so far done. But, for many minutes, the heart beat on with a muffled sound. This, however, did not vex me; it would not be heard through the wall. At length it ceased. The old man was dead.

NARRATOR removes the bed. Examines the corpse. Places his hand upon the heart and holds it there — many minutes. No pulsation.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I removed the bed and examined the corpse. Yes, he was stone, stone dead. I placed my hand upon the heart and held it there many minutes. There was no pulsation. He was stone dead. His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR, proud, almost cheerful.

NARRATOR
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The night wanes. Candlelight. NARRATOR works hastily, in silence — dismembers the corpse: head, arms, legs. A tub stands ready; it catches all. No stain on the floor.

He pries up three planks from the flooring, deposits the remains between the scantlings, replaces the boards with cunning care. Smooths the seams. Nothing wrong to the eye.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The night waned, and I worked hastily, but in silence. First of all I dismembered the corpse. I cut off the head and the arms and the legs. I then took up three planks from the flooring of the chamber, and deposited all between the scantlings. I then replaced the boards so cleverly, so cunningly, that no human eye—not even his—could have detected any thing wrong. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had caught all—ha! ha!

A distant BELL sounds four.

INT. HOUSE ENTRY - NIGHT

Still dark as midnight. A knocking at the street door. NARRATOR goes down with a light heart and opens it.

Three men in coats and badges: OFFICER REYNOLDS (older, measured), OFFICER HALE (broad, watchful), OFFICER BRENNAN (younger, polite). They enter with perfect suavity.

OFFICER REYNOLDS
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play has been aroused. We have been deputed to search the premises.

NARRATOR smiles — for what had he to fear?

NARRATOR
Gentlemen—welcome. The shriek was my own in a dream. The old man is absent in the country. Search—search well.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR leads them through. He shows the old man's treasures — secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of his confidence he brings chairs. He seats OFFICER REYNOLDS, OFFICER HALE, and OFFICER BRENNAN — and places his own seat upon the very spot beneath which reposes the corpse.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I led them, at length, to his chamber. I showed them his treasures, secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of my confidence, I brought chairs into the room, and desired them here to rest from their fatigues, while I myself, in the wild audacity of my perfect triumph, placed my own seat upon the very spot beneath which reposed the corpse of the victim.

The officers sit. They are satisfied. NARRATOR answers cheerily. They chat of familiar things.

OFFICER HALE
Quiet street, this. You're certain the old gentleman is in the country?

NARRATOR
Quite certain. You have searched well—you see how it is.

NARRATOR's face: singularly at ease — then, ere long, a faint pallor. He wishes them gone. A ringing in his ears.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The officers were satisfied. My manner had convinced them. I was singularly at ease. They sat, and while I answered cheerily, they chatted of familiar things. But, ere long, I felt myself getting pale and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears: but still they sat and still chatted.

The ringing becomes more distinct. NARRATOR talks more freely. The sound gains definiteness — until he knows it is not within his ears.

A low, dull, quick sound — such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. The HEARTBEAT, rising from under the floorboards.

NARRATOR goes very pale. He talks more fluently, with a heightened voice. The officers chat on, pleasant, smiling.

OFFICER BRENNAN
We won't trouble you much longer.

NARRATOR
No trouble—no trouble at all—

The heartbeat steadily increases. NARRATOR gasps for breath. The officers hear it not.

He talks more quickly — more vehemently. He rises and argues about trifles, high key, violent gesticulations.

NARRATOR
—and as I say, the shutters, the shutters are fastened every night, through fear of robbers—every night—

The noise steadily increases.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Why would they not be gone?

He paces the floor to and fro with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swears. Swings his chair and grates it upon the boards — but the noise arises over all.

Louder — louder — louder.

The men chat pleasantly and smile.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!—this I thought, and this I think. But anything was better than this agony! Anything was more tolerable than this derision! I could bear those hypocritical smiles no longer! I felt that I must scream or die! and now—again!—hark! louder! louder! louder! louder!

NARRATOR shrieks — on his feet, pointing at the floor.

NARRATOR
Villains! dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

The officers spring up. The heartbeat thunders. NARRATOR's face — broken, triumphant, mad with relief.

FADE OUT.

THE END
